name: Manchester University Academic Center
directions: second and third floor restrooms. on the second floor the gender neutral restroom replaces the women’s room on the left, and on the third floor it replaces the men’s room on the right. go up the stairs or elevator and it will be the first door down the hall. the restrooms on the first floor of the academic building are gendered.
comment: the gender neutral second floor restroom typically has lots of cis women in it, and the neutral third floor restroom usually has mostly cis men. sometimes clubs will use the sinks in both restrooms regardless of gender after classes are over for the day. the third floor gender neutral restroom has urinals and does not have trash cans in the stalls. the stalls in the second floor neutral restrooms have a bag hook, as well as trash cans. neither restrooms have a changing table, but there is space to put down a backpack.

name: Toronto Pan Am Sports Centre
directions: Multiple single-stall accessible + gender neutral washrooms all over the building. 3 are free-to-enter: 1 in the food court, and 2 in the main hall upon entrance. There are more beyond the turnstiles (need to have a TPASC membership or be a UofT student/staff to access), along with a universal change room.

name: University of Toronto Scarborough - Highland Hall
directions: On the bottom floor, there are two gender neutral (“Universal”) washrooms that have stalls with floor-length doors (and locks!). They are a tight fit, so I wouldn’t highly recommend for folks with accessibility needs. On the main floor, there are single-stall, neutral + accessible washrooms (“Universal”).

name: Women and Infants
directions: On the first floor right by the laboratory, there are 2 single-occupancy gender neutral bathrooms that have those vacant/occupied signs on the door. Ask security to point you there. They’re very safe restrooms tucked around the corner away from the main lobby.
comment: You can only get to these restrooms if you’re in the hospital for a reason, so that’s who this listing is for. Security issues a badge to every vendor/visitor who enters the building to keep people safe since there’s lots of babies there. They don’t want random people there for no reason typically

name: Pioneer Park
directions: Park in Memorial Drive or in Cowaramup townsite.  No dedicated accessible parking in Memorial Drive.  There is a bitumen path, but it's old and very narrow.  It's steep from Cowaramup townsite and may be difficult for people with mobility difficulty.
comment: 6 GENDERED SO stalls and one Universal Access.  UA has toilet with grab rails, lowered basin and hand dryer, and baby change table.  All doors and locks are manual, doors swing inward. Available 24/7, lit at night.  The park isn't lit but the area is very safe.  Park also has public BBQs and picnic tables and playground.
